    <worksheet xml:id="ws-matrixarithmetic" margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm"><title component="print-worksheets">Participate: Matrix Arithmetic</title><title component="online-worksheets">Participate</title>
      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Begin to view matrices as objects similar to numbers, which can be added, subtracted, and multiplied
              by a number.  
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Be able to perform matrix addition and multiplication by a number and use properties of these operations. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
</objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          We have discussed multiplying a matrix by a number.  Most texts will use the term <term>scalar</term>
          instead of <q>number</q>.  There are good reasons for this, but they are outside the scope of this material.  
          Still, it is good to recognize both words could be used.  
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Consider the matrices <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>B=\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
          Say why <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are not equal as matrix objects.  Does this make sense to you, or do you think
          they should be the same thing?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              They are not the same size, so they can't be equal as matrices.  However, they contain the exact same 
              information and the only difference is the orientation of the writing.  
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What do you think a <term>square matrix</term> is?  What about a <term>row matrix</term> or <term>column matrix</term>?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              A square matrix is <m>n\times n</m>, same number of rows as columns.  A row matrix is <m>1\times n</m>, written
              as one row, while a column matrix is <m>n\times 1</m>, written as one column.  
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Let <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 5 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              <m>B=\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp -3 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and 
              <m>C=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ -1 \amp 5 \\ -2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              Calculate each of the items below.  What do you notice about your answers?
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>A+B</m>, and <m>(A+B)+C</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <m>A+B=\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
                <m>(A+B)+C=\begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 2 \\ -1 \amp 7 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> 
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>B+C</m> and <m>A+(B+C)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <m>B+C=\begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
                <m>A+(B+C)=\begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 2 \\ -1 \amp 7 \\ -1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>5(A+B)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <m>5(A+B)=\begin{bmatrix} 25 \amp 10 \\ 0 \amp 10 \\ 5 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>5A</m>, <m>5B</m>, and <m>5A+5B</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <m>5A=\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 15 \\ 10 \amp 25 \\ -5 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              <m>5B=\begin{bmatrix} 20 \amp -5 \\ -10 \amp -15 \\ 10 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and 
              <m>5A+5B=\begin{bmatrix} 25 \amp 10 \\ 0 \amp 10 \\ 5 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task> 
        </exercise>

      </page>
      <page>
        <exercise>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              For each of the proposed properties below, say whether it is True, False, or 
              Insufficient Information and give a sentence or two of explanation/reasoning.  Note that these are all statements 
              you might be used to using with numbers, and the goal is to think about how matrices and numbers are similar in some ways and different in some ways.   
            </p>
            <p>
              Let <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>X</m> be matrices of the same size, and let <m>k</m> and <m>n</m>
              be numbers.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>A-B=A+(-B)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                True.  Discuss subtracting versus multiplying by <m>-1</m> and adding, possibly additive inverses.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(k+n)A = kA+nA</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                True, another distributive property.  
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>2A+X=B</m> then <m>X=2A-B</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                False, subtracting <m>2A</m> from both sides gives <m>X=B-2A</m>. 
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>2X=B</m> then <m>X=\frac{1}{2}B</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                True, multiplying both sides by the number <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>AX=B</m> then <m>X=\frac{1}{A}B</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Insufficient Information.  We don't yet know what multiplying by a matrix means, and certainly not
                what dividing by a matrix might mean.  
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>kB=Bk</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                True. Multiplying a matrix by a number in either order comes down to 
                multiplying the number entries together in either order, and number multiplication is commutative.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>AB=BA</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Insufficient information.  We don't yet know what multiplying by a matrix means.  This is true for numbers, however.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For each matrix <m>C</m>, there is a matrix <m>Z</m> such that <m>Z+C=C+Z=C</m>.  (The matrix
                      <m>Z</m> acts like the number <m>0</m> does for numbers.)
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                True, the zero matrix of the appropriate size.  But there are different zero matrices and only
                one number <m>0</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task workspace=".5in">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For each matrix <m>C</m>, there is a matrix <m>I</m> such that <m>IC=CI=C</m>. (The matrix
                      <m>I</m> acts like the number <m>1</m> does for numbers.)
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Insufficient Information.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
        </exercise>
        

      
      </page>
